                        <div class="c_presentation_info">
        
    <article class="presentation-info">

        <header>
            <h2 class="presentation-info-title">Ouch! That Stereotype Hurts: How to counter bias</h2>

                        <div class="arena-small-1 presentation-info-presenter">Dr. Denise O’Neil Green (Assistant Vice-President/Vice-Provost Equity, Diversity and Inclusion and the Office of EDI team)</div>
            
                        <div class="arena-small-1 presentation-info-folder">
                                <a href="https://ryecast.ryerson.ca/80/Home/index.aspx#?folderId=755" target="_self">Soup and Substance</a>
                            </div>
            
            <div class="arena-small-1 presentation-info-date">Tuesday, December 20, 2016, 2:42 PM</div>
        </header>

                <section class="arena-body-1 presentation-info-description">
            <p class="description-text" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top" title="When we hear a remark that is biased, stereotypical or a microaggression, we&#39;re often unsure what to say. Join the Office of Equity, Diversity and Inclusion to improve your skills speaking up against harmful attitudes and biased statements, as well as interrupting inappropriate comments. Participants will gain hands-on practice speaking up when they hear a derogatory comment or see other inappropriate behaviours. This will include six practical approaches that can be applied immediately at Ryerson. Attendees will leave feeling confident in their ability to say &quot;OUCH! That stereotype hurts!&quot; Dr. Denise O’Neil Green (Assistant Vice-President/Vice-Provost Equity, Diversity and Inclusion and the Office of EDI team) moderated the discussion."> When we hear a remark that is biased, stereotypical or a microaggression, we&#39;re often unsure what to say. Join the Office of Equity, Diversity and Inclusion to improve your skills speaking up against harmful attitudes and biased statements, as well as interrupting inappropriate comments. Participants will gain hands-on practice speaking up when they hear a derogatory comment or see other inappropriate behaviours. This will include six practical approaches that can be applied immediately at Ryerson. Attendees will leave feeling confident in their ability to say &quot;OUCH! That stereotype hurts!&quot; Dr. Denise O’Neil Green (Assistant Vice-President/Vice-Provost Equity, Diversity and Inclusion and the Office of EDI team) moderated the discussion. </p>
        </section>
        
